{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17202"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17202"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.18,0.12,0.51,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69367"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9892"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54820"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4122"},{"type":"tags","id":"4123"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48137"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69367"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of increasing lower abdominal pain and bloating. She reports early satiety and has lost 3 kg in weight. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago and is regular. She is sexually active with one partner and uses oral contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a firm, non-tender mass arising from the pelvis to the umbilicus. There is no ascites. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein: 890 \u00b5g/L (\u0026lt;10)\u003Cbr /\u003EBeta-human chorionic gonadotropin: 45 IU/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003Cbr /\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 450 U/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan shows a 15 cm right ovarian mass with no evidence of metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serous cystadenoma","Mature teratoma","Granulosa cell tumour","Mixed germ cell tumour","Dysgerminoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis young woman presents with a rapidly growing pelvic mass and elevated tumour markers, which is highly suggestive of a malignant ovarian germ cell tumour. The pattern of tumour markers is particularly helpful in determining the specific type.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed germ cell tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the elevation of both alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (\u03b2-hCG). The AFP elevation suggests yolk sac elements, while \u03b2-hCG elevation suggests choriocarcinoma or embryonal components. Mixed germ cell tumours commonly contain multiple histological elements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysgerminoma\u003C/strong\u003E, while being the most common malignant germ cell tumour, typically presents with elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) alone. AFP and \u03b2-hCG are usually normal unless there are other germ cell elements present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMature teratoma\u003C/strong\u003E is typically benign and does not produce elevated tumour markers. These tumours are often cystic and contain various tissue elements like hair, teeth, or sebaceous material.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulosa cell tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is a sex cord-stromal tumour that typically produces estradiol and inhibin, not AFP or \u03b2-hCG. These tumours often present with menstrual irregularities or postmenopausal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerous cystadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an epithelial ovarian tumour that is typically benign and does not produce elevated tumour markers. These tumours are more common in older women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of malignant germ cell tumours typically involves fertility-sparing surgery (unilateral salpingo-oophorectomy) followed by combination chemotherapy. The prognosis is generally excellent with modern treatment approaches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysgerminomas are the most common malignant ovarian germ cell tumour, typically presenting in young women with a rapidly growing pelvic mass.","Elevated serum alpha-fetoprotein suggests presence of yolk sac elements in a germ cell tumour.","Fertility-sparing surgery is appropriate for most young women with early-stage malignant ovarian germ cell tumours."],"references":["Practitioners TRAC of general. Australian Family Physician. The Royal Australian College of general Practitioners; [cited 2024 Dec 11]. Investigation and management of an ovarian mass. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/investigation-and-management-of-an-ovarian-mass"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54820"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17202"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54820"},"attributes":{"cr